<h3>Little=E2=80=99s Law</h3>
<p>Little=E2=80=99s Law connects the capacity of a queuing system, the aver=
age time spent in the system, and the average arrival rate into the system =
without knowing any other features of the queue. The formula is quite simpl=
e and is written as follows:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img title=3D"L=3D\lambda W" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex=
?\fn_jvn&amp;space;L=3D\lambda&amp;space;W" alt=3D""></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>or transformed to solve for the other two variables so that:<br><br></p>
<p><img title=3D"\lambda=3D\frac{L}{W}" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/p=
ng.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;\lambda=3D\frac{L}{W}" alt=3D""></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img title=3D"W=3D\frac{L}{\lambda}" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/p=
ng.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;W=3D\frac{L}{\lambda}" alt=3D""></p>
<p><br>Where:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong><em>L</em></strong> is the average number of customers in the s=
ystem</li>
<li><strong><em>=CE=BB</em></strong> (lambda) is the average arrival rate i=
nto the system</li>
<li><strong><em>W</em></strong> is the average amount of time spent in the =
system</li>
</ul>
<p>Project management processes like Lean and Kanban <a rel=3D"noopener nor=
eferrer" href=3D"https://www.process.st/littles-law/" target=3D"_blank">wou=
ldn=E2=80=99t exist</a> without the Little=E2=80=99s Law queuing models. Th=
ey=E2=80=99re critical for business applications, in which Little=E2=80=99s=
 Law can be written in plain English as:<br><br></p>
<p><img title=3D"Work\ in\ Progress=3DThroughput\ast Lead\ Time" src=3D"htt=
ps://latex.codecogs.com/gif.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;Work\&amp;space;in\&amp=
;space;Progress=3DThroughput\ast&amp;space;Lead\&amp;space;Time" alt=3D""><=
/p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img title=3D"Throughput=3D\frac{Work\ in\ Progress}{Lead\ Time}" src=3D=
"https://latex.codecogs.com/gif.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;Throughput=3D\frac{=
Work\&amp;space;in\&amp;space;Progress}{Lead\&amp;space;Time}" alt=3D""></p=
>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img title=3D"Lead\ Time=3D\frac{Work\ in\ Progress}{Throughput}" src=3D=
"https://latex.codecogs.com/gif.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;Lead\&amp;space;Tim=
e=3D\frac{Work\&amp;space;in\&amp;space;Progress}{Throughput}" alt=3D""><br=
><br></p>


                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container qhe=
ading">
                                           =20
<a class=3D"anchor" id=3D"queuing-theory-examples--types-of-queuing-models"=
></a>
<h4 class=3D" h- ">Queuing theory examples &amp; types of queuing models</h=
4>

                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container rte=
">
                                           =20


<p>Little=E2=80=99s Law gives powerful insights because it lets us solve fo=
r important variables like the average wait of in a queue or the number of =
customers in queue simply based on two other inputs.<br><br></p>
<h5><strong>A line at a cafe</strong></h5>
<p>For example, if you=E2=80=99re waiting in line at a Starbucks, Little=E2=
=80=99s Law can <a rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" href=3D"https://yorkesoftwar=
e.com/2017/10/27/wip-limits-and-velocity/" target=3D"_blank">estimate how l=
ong</a> it would take to get your coffee.</p>
<p>Assume there are 15 people in line, one server, and 2 people are served =
per minute. To estimate this, you=E2=80=99d use Little=E2=80=99s Law in the=
 form:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;\frac=
{L}{\lambda}=3DW" alt=3D"" title=3D"\frac{L}{\lambda}=3DW"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Showing that you could expect to wait 7.5 minutes for your coffee.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/gif.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;\frac=
{15\&amp;space;people\&amp;space;in\&amp;space;line}{2\&amp;space;people\&a=
mp;space;served\&amp;space;per\&amp;space;minute}&amp;space;=3D&amp;space;7=
.5\&amp;space;minutes\&amp;space;of\&amp;space;waiting" alt=3D"" title=3D"\=
frac{15\ people\ in\ line}{10\ people\ served\ per\ minute} =3D 7.5\ minute=
s\ of\ waiting"><br><br></p>


                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container qim=
age">
                                           =20




<figure><img alt=3D"Little's Law for line for coffee in a Starbucks" class=
=3D"" src=3D"https://queue-it.com/media/ouqf5u3e/starbucks-littles-law.jpg"=
 style=3D"-webkit-clip-path: url(#); clip-path: url(#);"><figcaption></figc=
aption></figure>

                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container rte=
">
                                           =20


<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><em>Image by </em><a rel=3D"noopener noref=
errer" href=3D"https://yorkesoftware.com/2017/10/27/wip-limits-and-velocity=
/" target=3D"_blank"><em>John Yorke</em></a><a rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" =
href=3D"https://pixabay.com/?utm_source=3Dlink-attribution&amp;utm_medium=
=3Dreferral&amp;utm_campaign=3Dimage&amp;utm_content=3D602745" target=3D"_b=
lank" data-anchor=3D"?utm_source=3Dlink-attribution&amp;utm_medium=3Dreferr=
al&amp;utm_campaign=3Dimage&amp;utm_content=3D602745"></a></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>
<h5><strong>A line in a virtual waiting room</strong></h5>
<p>At Queue-it, we <a href=3D"https://queue-it.com/end-user-experience/">sh=
ow visitors their wait time</a> in the online queue using a queuing model b=
ased on Little=E2=80=99s Law, adding in factors to account for no-shows and=
 re-entries:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?\fn_jvn&amp;space;\frac=
{L}{\lambda}\ast&amp;space;\frac{1-N}{1-R}=3DW" alt=3D"" title=3D"\frac{L}{=
\lambda}\ast \frac{1-N}{1-R}=3DW"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Where:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong><em>L</em></strong> is the number of users ahead in line</li>
<li><strong><em>=CE=BB</em></strong> (lambda) is rate of redirects to the w=
ebsite or app, in users per minute</li>
<li><em><strong>N</strong> </em>is the no-show ratio</li>
<li><em><strong>R</strong> </em>is the re-entry rate to the queue</li>
<li><strong><em>W</em></strong> is the estimated wait time, in minutes<br><=
br></li>
</ul>
<h5><strong>Military process optimization</strong></h5>
<p>We can look at a process optimization example from the military, courtes=
y of <a rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" href=3D"https://www.process.st/littles-=
law/" target=3D"_blank">Process.st</a>.</p>
<p>In this <a rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" href=3D"https://www.isixsigma.com=
/implementation/case-studies/u-s-a-f-uses-continuous-process-improvement-on=
-the-b-2-bomber-part-1/" target=3D"_blank">real-life example</a>, the milit=
ary needed to determine the ideal amount of time B-2 stealth bombers would =
be in maintenance. There are only 20 B-2 aircraft and they need to be ready=
 at a moment=E2=80=99s notice. But they require frequent maintenance, which=
 can range anywhere from 18 to 45 days.</p>
<p>Using Little=E2=80=99s Law helps find the balance of aircraft in use ver=
sus aircraft under maintenance.</p>


                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container qim=
age">
                                           =20




<figure><img alt=3D"B-2 stealth bomber plane" class=3D"" src=3D"https://que=
ue-it.com/media/m0gljeso/b-2-stealth-bomber.jpg" style=3D"-webkit-clip-path=
: url(#); clip-path: url(#);"><figcaption></figcaption></figure>

                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container rte=
">
                                           =20


<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><em>Image by skeeze from <a rel=3D"noopene=
r noreferrer" href=3D"https://pixabay.com/?utm_source=3Dlink-attribution&am=
p;utm_medium=3Dreferral&amp;utm_campaign=3Dimage&amp;utm_content=3D602745" =
target=3D"_blank" data-anchor=3D"?utm_source=3Dlink-attribution&amp;utm_med=
ium=3Dreferral&amp;utm_campaign=3Dimage&amp;utm_content=3D602745">Pixabay</=
a></em></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>
<p>Based on flight schedule analysis, it was calculated that&nbsp;three B-2=
 bombers&nbsp;would be&nbsp;under maintenance&nbsp;at any given time. The r=
ate at which&nbsp;bombers entered maintenance&nbsp;was also calculated to b=
e&nbsp;roughly every 7 days. So:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>L</strong>=3D number of items in WIP (maintenance) =3D&nbsp;3</=
li>
<li><strong>A</strong>=3D arrival/departure rate =3D 1 every 7 days =3D&nbs=
p;1/7 days</li>
<li><strong>W</strong>=3D the average amount of time spent in maintenance =
=3D&nbsp;???</li>
</ul>
<p>Put into Little=E2=80=99s Law, this leaves us with:</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://queue-it.com/media/0ikhsxhf/queuing-model-example-mi=
litary.jpg?width=3D178&amp;height=3D88&amp;mode=3Dmax" alt=3D"" width=3D"17=
8" height=3D"88"></p>
<p>Therefore, the&nbsp;target lead time&nbsp;for B-2 bomber maintenance nee=
ded to be&nbsp;21 days&nbsp;to meet the demands of both available aircraft =
and the regular flight schedules.<br><br></p>


                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container qhe=
ading">
                                           =20
<a class=3D"anchor" id=3D"6-how-does-queue-psychology-impact-queuing"></a>
<h2 class=3D" h- ">6. How does queue psychology impact queuing?</h2>

                                        </div>
                                        <div class=3D"control-container rte=
">
                                           =20


<p>Queuing theory is helpful in explaining the math behind how queues run. =
But when queues involve humans, queue psychology is important to understand=
 the queue experience as well.</p>
<p>Queue psychology research shows it=E2=80=99s not the length of the wait =
that determines how positive or negative the queue experience is, but rathe=
r how people <em>feel</em> while waiting.</p>
<p><strong>Related: </strong><a href=3D"https://queue-it.com/blog/psycholog=
y-of-queuing/"><strong>The Psychology of Queuing Revealed in 6 Simple Rules=
</strong></a></p>
<p>For example, unoccupied time feels longer than occupied time. Distractio=
ns or the ability to do something else while in line makes time feel like i=
t goes by faster. And uncertain waits feel longer than known, finite waits.=
</p>
<p>That=E2=80=99s why the callback option on customer service lines is so p=
opular. You can feel the anxiety go down when you get the option to be call=
ed back in 10 minutes, freeing you to do something else instead of listenin=
g to that terrible muzak for an unknown amount of time.</p>
<p>For queuing situations involving people=E2=80=94like websites that use a=
n <a title=3D"online queuing system" href=3D"https://queue-it.com/online-qu=
euing-system/">online queuing system</a>=E2=80=94the psychological rules go=
verning the queues are just as important as the mathematical ones.</p>
<p><br><em>(This blog has been updated since it was written in 2020).</em><=
/p>


